gist: >
  This guide teaches implementation patterns for production React apps on
  Vercel, with an emphasis on server components, server actions, and cache
  strategy. It explains when interactivity should move to client components
  and how to keep most rendering server-side for lower bundle cost. It also
  covers image and font optimization, route segment structure, and common
  deployment mistakes that hurt performance.

voice_brief:
  script: >
    When you're building React on Vercel, the biggest unlock is thinking
    server-first instead of client-first. Start with server components as
    the default and only opt into client components where you actually need
    browser-side state or event handlers. That one decision keeps your
    JavaScript payload smaller and your pages faster. For writes and form
    submissions, use server actions so your mutation logic stays close to
    your rendering flow instead of spreading across many API routes.
    Caching is the next lever: you get request deduplication during render,
    persistent data cache behavior, and route-level caching choices that can
    massively improve response time. On top of that, use next/image and
    next/font so media and typography stay fast without layout shift. The
    point of these patterns is to make performance the default, not an
    afterthought, while keeping the codebase easier for teams to evolve.
